potential  and its quasinormal modes of a massless
scalar in the Schwarzschild black hole background. The ingoing
wave () at the event horizon and the outgoing wave
() at infinity denote  quasinormal modes. 

 [t!]
 
file=fig6.eps,width=0.7  The
quasinormal modes in AdS space. These are denoted by purely
ingoing modes () at the event horizon. 


In asymptotically  AdS space, these modes are
 defined as the solutions which are purely ingoing wave
() at the event horizon and
which vanish () at infinity (see Fig.6). This
comes from the boundary condition that the wave function is zero
at infinity because its potential is infinite at infinity. Because
one cannot find any travelling wave at infinity, we can extend
this definition to the flux boundary condition in AdS space : the
ingoing flux  at the event horizon and no
flux () at infinity. Then there are two ways to
obtain  with the complex frequency. First one
chooses  to get the quasinormal modes. These impose the
restriction as  c-a=-n,  c-b=-n,where
(negative integers). Considering Eq.()
leads to  _1= - l  -2i l 
(n+1 2  +1+(ml)^2  2  ),
_2= l  -2i l  (n+1 2 
+1+(ml)^2  2  ). Second from ,
one finds  which lead to  _3=
- l  +2i l  (n+1 2 
-1+(ml)^2  2  ),
_4= l  +2i l  (n+1 2 
-1+(ml)^2  2  ). When decomposing the
quasinormal frequencies  into  real and imaginary parts :
,  should be positive for all
quasinormal frequencies because  those modes decay with time.
Hence the true quasinormal frequencies are given by
Eqs.() and () but not by Eqs.()
and (). We note that in calculating quasinormal modes
in AdS space, one has to use a definition of the zero-flux at
infinity. Someone uses the Dirichlet boundary condition on the
wave function at infinity which eventually leads to . A
single term of either normalizable one or nonnormalizable one
leads to zero-flux at infinity. But requiring the Dirichlet
condition (no nonnormalizable term) at infinity leads to a correct
definition of quasinormal frequencies.



AdS/CFT correspondence 
The complex quasinormal frequencies describe the decay of the
massive scalar perturbation in the background of AdS-black hole.
These depend on the parameter of the black hole () as
well as the parameters of perturbed field (). In terms of
the AdS/CFT correspondence, an off-equilibrium configuration in
the AdS space (BTZ black hole with ) is related to an
off-equilibrium thermal state in the boundary conformal field
theory. The timescale for the decay of scalar perturbation is
given by the imaginary part of the quasinormal frequencies
(). Using the AdS/CFT correspondence, one can obtain a
prediction of the timescale for return to equilibrium of its dual
CFT. Actually there is a precise agreement between quasinormal
modes on the bulk side and the location of the poles for the
retarded correlation function describing the linear response of an
perturbing operator  on the CFT side. This
provides a new quantitative test for the thermal AdS/CFT
correspondence. Further, expressing  as
, where
 is the Choptuik scaling parameter, it suggests a deeper
connection between the critical phenomena of the BTZ black hole
thermodynamics and quasinormal modes. According to the
thermal AdS/CFT correspondence, this leads to the boundary CFT
interpretation of Choptiuk scaling (a universal scaling behavior).

 wave equation in de Sitter space 

dS wave equation 

We start with the wave equation for a massive scalar
field(_dS ^2 -m^2) _dS =0
 in the background of three dimensional de Sitter
space ds_dS ^2=-(1- r^2 l^2  ) dt^2 + (1-
r^2 l^2  )^-1 dr^2 +r^2 d^2.  Here
 is the curvature radius of de Sitter space and hereafter we
set  for simplicity unless otherwise stated. The above metric
is singular at the cosmological horizon  which divides
space into four regions, as is shown in Fig.7.
 
 
file=fig7.eps,width=0.4  The global
structure of de Sitter spacetime. This diagram looks like that of
the BTZ black hole with   except replacing 
here by  in Fig. 3. But the difference is that the
causally connected region (shaded SD) in this figure is compact,
whereas the causally connected region (shaded region: SR) in Fig.
3 is noncompact. Hence we expect that the assumed  dS/CFT
correspondence which is usually defined in the FT or PT including
 is not established in the SD where is causally
disconnected to the FT and PT. 
There are two regions with  which correspond to the
causal diamonds of observers at the north and south poles :
northern diamond (ND) and southern diamond (SD). An observer at
 is surrounded by a cosmological horizon at . Two
regions with  containing the future-null
infinity  and past-null infinity   are
called future triangle (FT) and past triangle (PT), respectively.
A timelike Killing vector  is
future-directed only in the southern diamond. To obtain the
greybody factor, we have to obtain a definite wave propagation as
time evolves. Hence  we confine ourselves to the southern diamond
(shaded region). This means that our working space is compact, in
contrast to the AdS case of the BTZ black hole.

In connection with the assumed dS/CFT correspondence, one may
classify the mass-squared  into three cases:
. For a massive scalar with  ,
one has a non-unitary CFT. A scalar with mass  can be
related to a unitary CFT.  A massless scalar with  is
special and it would be treated separately. Here we consider only
 as a parameter at the beginning. Assuming a mode
